  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from their unlawful activities and integrate these profits into the legitimate financial system, which can fund further criminal activities and undermine the integrity of financial institutions.\n\nIn China, the fight against money laundering is taken very seriously. The country has established a comprehensive legal framework to combat money laundering, including the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which was enacted in 2007. This law sets out the obligations of financial institutions to prevent and detect money laundering activities and provides for the investigation and prosecution of such crimes. The People's Bank of China and other regulatory bodies are also actively involved in monitoring and enforcing compliance with anti-money laundering regulations.\n\nIndividuals and entities found guilty of money laundering can face severe penalties, including substantial fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. The Chinese government is committed to maintaining the stability and integrity of its financial system and works in cooperation with international counterparts to combat money laundering globally.",
